Here's how to save/restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**In `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and use a custom Window subclass:**

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new NotePage());
}
```

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is NotePage note)
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

1. **`OnStopped`** fires when the app is fully backgrounded — save here.
2. **`OnResumed`** fires when returning from background — restore here.
3. **`OnDestroying`** also saves because Android's back button can skip `Stopped`.
4. **Use `Preferences`** for small string values — it's fast enough to avoid ANR timeouts (~5s on Android).
5. **`Resumed` does NOT fire on first launch** — load any persisted draft in your page's constructor or `OnAppearing` instead.
